'''Davinson Sánchez Mina''' (born 12 June 1996) is a Colombian professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[centre-back]] for {{Turkish football updater|Galatasaray}} club [[Galatasaray S.K. (football)|Galatasaray]] and the [[Colombia national football team|Colombia national team]].

Sánchez began his career in Colombia with [[Atlético Nacional]], where he made his professional debut in [[2013 Categoría Primera A season|2013]] and went on to win four [[Categoría Primera A]] titles, two [[Copa Colombia]] trophies ([[2012 Copa Colombia|2012]], [[2013 Copa Colombia|2013]]), the [[2016 Superliga Colombiana]], and the [[2016 Copa Libertadores]]. In [[2016–17 AFC Ajax season|2016–17]], he moved to Europe to join [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]], where he was named the club's Player of the Year and reached the [[2017 UEFA Europa League Final]]. Later in [[2017–18 Tottenham Hotspur F.C. season|2017]], he signed for [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] in a then club-record £42 million transfer, making over 200 appearances. In [[2023–24 Süper Lig|2023]], he joined Turkish [[Süper Lig]] club [[Galatasaray S.K. (football)|Galatasaray]], where he won the [[Turkish Super Cup]] in [[2023 Turkish Super Cup|2023]], the [[Süper Lig]] in [[2023–24 Süper Lig|2023–24]] and [[2024–25 Süper Lig|2024–25]], and the [[Turkish Cup]] in [[2024–25 Turkish Cup|2024–25]].

At youth level, Sánchez represented [[Colombia national under-17 football team|Colombia]] at the [[2013 South American U-17 Championship]] and was part of the [[Colombia national under-20 football team|Colombia]] squads that participated at the [[2015 South American U-20 Championship]] and the [[2015 FIFA U-20 World Cup]], respectively. He made his senior debut for Colombia in 2016 and has represented the nation at three editions of the [[Copa América]], as well as at the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]].

== Club career ==
=== Atlético Nacional ===
Davinson Sánchez began his footballing education in the academy of [[América de Cali]], first as a defensive midfielder before being moved permanently to [[centre-back]] due to his anticipation, strength and aerial ability.<ref>{{cite news |title=La historia de Davinson Sánchez, defensa colombiano del Tottenham |url=https://www.futbolred.com/colombianos-exterior/la-historia-de-davinson-sanchez-defensa-colombiano-del-tottenham-87703 |work=Futbolred |language=es}}</ref> During his early teens he impressed playing above his age category, drawing interest from clubs in Medellín.<ref>{{cite news |title=Davinson Sánchez, el jugador colombiano que se impone en Europa |url=https://www.elpais.com.co/deportes/davinson-sanchez-el-jugador-colombiano-que-se-impone-en-europa.html |work=El País |location=Cali |language=es}}</ref>

After his family relocated to Antioquia, Sánchez joined the youth setup of [[Atlético Nacional]] under coach [[Juan Carlos Osorio]], who promoted a possession-based system relying on ball-playing centre-backs.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Comentarios4 |last2=Comentarios4 |last3=Compartido |last4=Compartido |date=2016-03-16 |title=No hay título que se le resista a Davinson Sánchez |url=https://e01-marca.uecdn.es/futbol/colombia/2016/03/16/56e9b8ece2704e12048b4631.html |access-date=2025-11-04 |website=Marca.com |language=es}}</ref>  
He made his professional debut on 27 October 2013, playing the full 90 minutes in a 1–0 loss to [[Boyacá Chicó F.C.|Boyacá Chicó]] in the [[Categoría Primera A]].<ref name="auto">{{Cite web |title=Live Soccer Scores, Fixtures, Results & Tables {{!}} Soccerway |url=https://www.soccerway.com/ |access-date=2025-11-04 |website=www.soccerway.com |language=en}}</ref>

On 2 March 2016 he scored his first senior goal in a 3–0 win over [[Sporting Cristal]] during the [[Copa Libertadores]] group stage.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Atl. Nacional - Sporting Cristal 3:0 |url=https://www.soccerway.com/match/atl-nacional-C23omttL/sporting-cristal-rVwaK9XN/ |access-date=2025-11-04 |website=www.soccerway.com |language=en}}</ref>  
That year he was a starter throughout Nacional's victorious [[2016 Copa Libertadores]], including both legs of the final against [[Independiente del Valle]], giving Nacional its second continental title.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2019-05-09 |title=La extraordinaria carrera de Davinson Sánchez: mundialista, campeón de Copa Libertadores y finalista de Europa League y de la Champions League |url=https://cnnespanol.cnn.com/2019/05/09/la-extraordinaria-carrera-de-davinson-sanchez-mundialista-campeon-de-copa-libertadores-y-finalista-de-europa-league-y-de-la-champions-league |access-date=2025-11-04 |website=CNN |language=es}}</ref>

His performances in the Copa Libertadores caught the attention of European and Brazilian clubs including [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]], [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]] and [[CR Flamengo|Flamengo]]. Sánchez declined Barcelona's offer because it required joining [[FC Barcelona Atlètic|Barcelona B]], opting for Ajax as he would be guaranteed valuable playing time.<ref>{{cite news |title=El Barcelona sigue a Davinson Sánchez |url=https://www.marca.com/futbol/barcelona/2016/05/27/57483a34e5fdeac0438b4582.html |work=Marca |language=es}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=IS richt bloedbad aan in supporterscafé van Real: zeker 16 doden {{!}} Voetbalzone |url=https://www.voetbalzone.nl/nieuws/is-richt-bloedbad-aan-in-supporterscafe-van-real-zeker-doden/277797 |access-date=2025-11-04 |website=www.voetbalzone.nl |language=nl}}</ref>

=== AFC Ajax ===
After winning the [[2016 Copa Libertadores]] with [[Atlético Nacional]], Sánchez signed a five-year contract with [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]] in June 2016 for a reported fee of €5&nbsp;million.<ref>https://english.ajax.nl/articles/ajax-signs-colombian-davinson-sanchez/</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Ajax haalt Colombiaan Davinson Sánchez |url=https://www.telegraaf.nl/sport/539063/ajax-haalt-colombiaan-davinson-sanchez |work=De Telegraaf |language=nl}}</ref> He officially joined the Dutch club in late July following Nacional's continental campaign and was unveiled alongside compatriot [[Mateo Cassierra]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=One moment, please... |url=http://hsbnoticias.com/noticias/deportes/f%C3%BAtbol/oficial-atletico-nacional-cede-davinson-sanchez-al-ajax-pe-217299 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241130103237/http://hsbnoticias.com/noticias/deportes/f%C3%BAtbol/oficial-atletico-nacional-cede-davinson-sanchez-al-ajax-pe-217299 |archive-date=2024-11-30 |access-date=2025-11-04 |website=hsbnoticias.com |language=en}}</ref>

==== 2016–17 season ====
Sánchez made his competitive debut for Ajax on 13 August 2016 in a 2–2 draw away to [[Roda JC Kerkrade|Roda JC]] in the [[Eredivisie]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Cambuur - Den Bosch 0:1 |url=https://www.soccerway.com/match/cambuur-QRyYgO7J/den-bosch-4IzxgrNP/ |access-date=2025-11-04 |website=www.soccerway.com |language=en}}</ref>  
He quickly established himself as a starting centre-back under manager [[Peter Bosz]], known for his composure on the ball and aerial ability.

His first goal came on 24 September 2016, scoring from close range in a 5–1 league win against [[PEC Zwolle]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Ajax overklast PEC Zwolle met aanvallend voetbal |url=https://www.vi.nl/nieuws/ajax-overklast-pec-zwolle-met-aanvallend-voetbal |work=Voetbal International |language=nl}}</ref> He scored again on 20 November 2016, heading in from a corner in a 5–0 victory over [[N.E.C. (football club)|NEC Nijmegen]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Venlo - Jong Ajax 1:4 |url=https://www.soccerway.com/match/jong-ajax-GncWwxTm/venlo-UNA6IKFC/ |access-date=2025-11-04 |website=www.soccerway.com |language=en}}</ref> His third league goal came on 12 March 2017 in a 3–0 home win against [[FC Twente]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Mattersburg - Admira 0:1 |url=https://www.soccerway.com/match/admira-Yk4H6LHn/mattersburg-EepQ4ctk/ |access-date=2025-11-04 |website=www.soccerway.com |language=en}}</ref> Sánchez also scored in European competition on 24 November 2016, netting Ajax's second goal in a 2–0 win over [[Panathinaikos F.C.|Panathinaikos]] in the [[UEFA Europa League]] group stage.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ajax vs Panathinaikos |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/match/2019641--ajax-vs-panathinaikos/ |publisher=UEFA |date=24 November 2016 }}</ref>

In total, he made 43 appearances and scored 6 goals across all competitions — 32 in the Eredivisie and 11 in European competition — as Ajax finished second in the league and reached the [[2016–17 UEFA Europa League|UEFA Europa League Final]] against [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]], losing 2–0.<ref>{{cite news |last=Wilson |first=Jonathan |title=Ajax’s Davinson Sánchez, the Colombian backbone of youth movement |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/may/24/ajaxs-davinson-sanchez-the-colombian-backbone-of-youth-movement |work=The Guardian |date=24 May 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Davinson Sánchez on the rise at Ajax amid Barcelona links |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/ajax-amsterdam/story/3123161/davinson-sanchez-on-the-rise-at-ajax-amid-barcelona-links |work=ESPN }}</ref>  
His performances earned him Ajax’s Player of the Year award, putting Sánchez on the radar of major European clubs, including renewed interest from Barcelona as well as [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Gill |first=Stephen |date=2017-05-08 |title=Colombia's Davinson Sanchez 'player of the year' after 1st year at Dutch giants Ajax |url=https://colombiareports.com/colombia-defender-scoops-player-year-award-dutch-giants-ajax/ |access-date=2025-11-04 |website=Colombia News |language=en-US}}</ref>

==== 2017–18 season (departure) ====
Sánchez began pre-season with Ajax and made two competitive appearances at the start of the 2017–18 campaign — one in the Eredivisie and one in the [[UEFA Europa League]] qualifying rounds.<ref name="auto"/>  
However, following Tottenham's approach in August 2017, he was omitted from the matchday squad until the transfer was finalised. He departed Ajax having scored 7 goals in 45 official matches for the club in all competitions.

=== Tottenham Hotspur ===
On 18 August 2017, [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] announced the signing of Sánchez from [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]] for a club-record fee of £42&nbsp;million, making him the first Colombian to play for the club.<ref>{{Cite news |date=2017-08-23 |title=Davinson Sanchez: Tottenham complete signing of Ajax defender on six-year deal |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41031823 |access-date=2025-11-04 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Club announcement: Davinson Sánchez |url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/2017/august/club-announcement-davinson-sanchez/ |publisher=Tottenham Hotspur F.C. }}</ref>

==== 2017–18 season ====
Sánchez debuted in the [[Premier League]] on 27 August 2017, coming on in a 1–1 draw against [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley]].<ref>{{Cite news |date=2017-08-25 |title=Tottenham Hotspur 1-1 Burnley |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40990430 |access-date=2025-11-04 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref>  
Under [[Mauricio Pochettino]], he quickly became a regular starter on the right of a back three alongside [[Toby Alderweireld]] and [[Jan Vertonghen]]. He made 31 league appearances and nine in other competitions (five in the [[UEFA Champions League]] and four in domestic cups). Tottenham finished third and qualified for the Champions League again.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Gillett |first=Francesca |date=2017-08-29 |title=Great Ormond Street charity staff 'even more determined' to raise money after Charlie Gard |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/london/great-ormond-street-hospital-charity-workers-even-more-determined-to-raise-funds-after-charlie-gard-case-a3622356.html |access-date=2025-11-04 |website=The Standard |language=en}}</ref>

==== 2018–19 season ====
In May 2018, Sánchez extended his contract to 2024.<ref>{{cite web |title=Davinson Sánchez signs new contract |url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/2018/may/davinson-sanchez-signs-new-contract/ |publisher=Tottenham Hotspur F.C. }}</ref> On 10 February 2019, he scored his first goal for Tottenham, heading in from a [[Christian Eriksen]] corner during a 3–1 win over [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Wilson |first=Jeremy |last2=Tweedale |first2=Alistair |date=2019-02-10 |title=Spurs ride their luck to beat profligate Leicester after Jamie Vardy misses penalty with first touch |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2019/02/10/tottenham-vs-leicester-premier-league-live-score-latest-updates/ |access-date=2025-11-04 |work=The Telegraph |language=en-GB |issn=0307-1235}}</ref>

That same season he featured in Tottenham's historic run to the [[2018–19 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League Final]] against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], playing throughout the group and knockout stages.<ref>{{Cite web |last=UEFA.com |title=The official website for European football |url=https://www.uefa.com/errors/ |access-date=2025-11-04 |website=UEFA.com |language=en}}</ref>

==== 2019–20 season ====
After [[José Mourinho]] succeeded Pochettino in November 2019, Sánchez remained a central defensive regular and passed 100 total appearances for Tottenham.<ref>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Ben |title=José Mourinho’s Tottenham and Davinson Sánchez’s role |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/nov/25/jose-mourinho-tottenham-davinson-sanchez-enforcer |work=The Guardian |date=25 November 2019 }}</ref>

He made 27 league appearances plus ten in other competitions, including the [[UEFA Champions League]], helping Spurs finish sixth in the Premier League and qualify for the [[UEFA Europa League]].

==== 2020–21 season ====
Sánchez began the campaign rotating with [[Eric Dier]], [[Toby Alderweireld]], and [[Joe Rodon]]. On 10 February 2021 he scored twice in a 5–4 defeat to [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] in the fifth round of the [[FA Cup]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Hunter |first=Andy |date=2021-02-10 |title=Bernard strike sinks Spurs in extra time as Everton edge FA Cup thriller |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2021/feb/10/everton-tottenham-hotspur-fa-cup-fifth-round-match-report |access-date=2025-11-04 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>

He played 26 matches and scored two goals in all competitions, including appearances in the [[UEFA Europa League]]. Tottenham reached the [[EFL Cup]] final that season but were defeated by [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]].

==== 2021–22 season ====
Following the arrival of [[Antonio Conte]], Sánchez featured regularly as the right-sided centre-back in a back three. He scored a 96th-minute header in a 1–0 away win over [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] on 1 January 2022 from a [[Son Heung-min]] free-kick,<ref>{{cite news |title=Davinson Sánchez: Tottenham defender joins Galatasaray |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/59793926 |work=BBC Sport }}</ref> and also found the net against [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] in December 2021.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/tottenham-hotspur-vs-norwich-city/stats/446032|title=Champions League Qualifying (Sky Sports)|website=Sky Sports}}</ref>  
He made 32 appearances in all competitions, scoring twice, as Tottenham finished fourth and qualified for the Champions League.<ref>{{Cite news |date=2022-05-20 |title=Burnley 1-2 Newcastle: Callum Wilson scores twice as Clarets are relegated to Championship |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/61453542 |access-date=2025-11-04 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref>

==== 2022–23 season ====
During his final season, Sánchez made 24 appearances across all competitions, including the Champions League group stage.<ref>{{cite news |title=Davinson Sanchez Nearing Exit from Spurs in Summer Transfer |url=https://onefootball.com/de/news/davinson-sanchez-nearing-exit-from-spurs-in-summer-transfer-37878922 |work=OneFootball |date=13 July 2023 }}</ref> He captained Tottenham for the first time in an FA Cup tie against [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]].
  
By the end of his six-year tenure, Sánchez had made 207 competitive appearances and scored five goals for the club before transferring to [[Galatasaray S.K. (football)|Galatasaray]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Davinson Sánchez transfer |url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/2023/september/davinson-sanchez-transfer/ |publisher=Tottenham Hotspur F.C. }}</ref>

=== Galatasaray ===
On 4 September 2023, Turkish champions [[Galatasaray S.K. (football)|Galatasaray]] announced the permanent signing of Davinson Sánchez from Tottenham Hotspur for a reported €9.5 million fee, payable over several years, together with the loan of his former Spurs teammate Tanguy Ndombele.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Davinson Sanchez Mina Galatasaray'da! |url=https://www.galatasaray.org/haber/gs-sportif-a-s/davinson-sanchez-mina-galatasarayda/53863 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250509042138/https://www.galatasaray.org/haber/gs-sportif-a-s/davinson-sanchez-mina-galatasarayda/53863 |archive-date=2025-05-09 |access-date=2025-11-04 |website=www.galatasaray.org}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Media |first=P. A. |date=2023-09-04 |title=Davinson Sánchez and Ndombele leave Tottenham to join Galatasaray |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/sep/04/davinson-sanchez-tanguy-ndombele-tottenham-galatasaray-transfers |access-date=2025-11-04 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Ndombele, Sanchez join Galatasaray from Spurs |url=https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/ndombele-sanchez-join-galatasaray-spurs-2023-09-05/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230929162626/https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/ndombele-sanchez-join-galatasaray-spurs-2023-09-05/ |archive-date=2023-09-29 |access-date=2025-11-04 |work=Reuters |language=en-US}}</ref> Tottenham confirmed his departure the same day, noting that he had made over 200 competitive appearances for the London club before the move.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Davinson moves to Galatasaray |url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/2023/september/davinson-moves-to-galatasaray/ |access-date=2025-11-04 |website=Tottenham Hotspur |language=en}}</ref>

==== 2023–24 season ====
Sánchez was registered to reinforce Galatasaray's defence for the [[2023–24 Süper Lig]] and the [[2023–24 UEFA Champions League group stage]], joining a back line that already included [[Abdülkerim Bardakcı]] and [[Victor Nelsson]]. He made his league debut in September 2023, shortly after signing, and was quickly used by coach [[Okan Buruk]] for his recovery pace and experience in high-level European matches.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-09-05 |title=Tottenham's Sanchez, Ndombele join Galatasaray |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/38329810/tottenham-davinson-sanchez-tanguy-ndombele-join-galatasaray |access-date=2025-11-04 |website=ESPN.com |language=en}}</ref>

Sánchez scored his first goal for Galatasaray on 7 October in an away match against [[Antalyaspor]], finishing inside the area after a cross from [[Mauro Icardi]] to give Galatasaray a 1–0 lead; Icardi later added the second to seal a 2–0 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Antalyaspor 0-2 Galatasaray (Oct 7, 2023) Final Score |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/match/_/gameId/683207/galatasaray-antalyaspor |access-date=2025-11-04 |website=ESPN |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Antalyaspor vs. Galatasaray - Final Score - October 07, 2023 |url=https://www.foxsports.com/soccer/turkish-super-lig-antalyaspor-vs-galatasaray-oct-07-2023-game-boxscore-127023 |access-date=2025-11-04 |website=www.foxsports.com |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.footballwebpages.co.uk/match/2023-2024/turkish-super-lig/antalyaspor/galatasaray/479192|title=Turkish Süper Lig &#124; Antalyaspor 0 - 2 Galatasaray &#124; 2023-2024 &#124; Football Web Pages}}</ref>

During the same month, Sánchez started in Galatasaray's 3–2 away win over Manchester United in the Champions League, playing on the right of a two-man central defence; the Turkish champions came from behind twice and won through a late goal from Icardi.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Hytner |first=David |date=2023-10-03 |title=Manchester United agony goes on after Casemiro red and Galatasaray winner |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/oct/03/manchester-united-galatasaray-champions-league-match-report |access-date=2025-11-04 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=McVeigh |first=Niall |date=2023-10-03 |title=Manchester United 2-3 Galatasaray: Champions League – as it happened |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2023/oct/03/manchester-united-galatasaray-champions-league-live-updates |access-date=2025-11-04 |work=the Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>

Sánchez remained in the starting rotation through the spring of 2024 and was part of the squad that clinched Galatasaray's 24th Turkish league title with a 3–1 win over [[Konyaspor]] on 26 May 2024, finishing ahead of [[Fenerbahçe S.K. (football)|Fenerbahçe]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Galatasaray claim 24th Turkish League Title |url=https://www.galatasaray.org/en/haber/football/galatasaray-claim-24th-turkish-league-title/55603 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250322020550/https://www.galatasaray.org/en/haber/football/galatasaray-claim-24th-turkish-league-title/55603 |archive-date=2025-03-22 |access-date=2025-11-04 |website=www.galatasaray.org}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Galatasaray Won Trendyol Super League 2023-2024 Season -   TFF |url=https://www.tff.org/default.aspx?ftxtID=44405&pageID=471 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250219080201/https://www.tff.org/default.aspx?ftxtID=44405&pageID=471 |archive-date=2025-02-19 |access-date=2025-11-04 |website=www.tff.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Galatasaray clinch 24th Turkish title with 3-1 victory |url=https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/galatasaray-clinch-24th-turkish-title-with-3-1-victory-2024-05-26/ |work=Reuters |date=26 May 2024 }}</ref>
<ref>{{Cite web |title=TRT World - Galatasaray win Turkish Super Lig title |url=https://www.trtworld.com/article/18166582 |access-date=2025-11-04 |website=www.trtworld.com |language=en}}</ref> For that season he finished with one league goal (vs Antalyaspor), several starts in the league and Champions League, and a domestic league triumph.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Galatasaray win Turkish Super Lig title |url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/sports/galatasaray-win-turkish-super-lig-title/3231149 |access-date=2025-11-04 |website=www.aa.com.tr}}</ref>

==== 2024–25 season ====
Sánchez entered the [[2024–25 Süper Lig]] as an established starter for Okan Buruk alongside Bardakcı, with Galatasaray looking to defend their title and return to the [[UEFA Champions League]] league phase. Turkish outlets in late 2024 noted that he continued to start regularly but also served a one-match suspension in November due to yellow-card accumulation.<ref name="auto1">{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/errors/|title=The official website for European football|website=UEFA.com}}</ref>

Galatasaray went on to retain the league, giving Sánchez back-to-back Süper Lig titles with the club.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://talksport.com/football/3216441/fernando-muslera-penalty-galatasaray-turkish-super-lig-title/|title=Galatasaray goalkeeper scores in rare moment during league title-winning match|date=18 May 2025|website=talkSPORT}}</ref>

==== 2025–26 season ====
In August 2025, Sánchez extended his contract with Galatasaray by four years, committing his future to the club until 2029 with an option for an additional year after reportedly turning down several offers from other teams.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tribuna.com/en/news/2025-07-16-como-near-signing-galatasaray-defender-davinson-sanchez/|title=Como near signing Galatasaray defender, Davinson Sanchez|first=Olga|last=Melnikova|date=16 July 2025|website=Tribuna.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tribuna.com/en/news/2025-05-01-fiorentina-eye-former-tottenham-defender-davinson-sanchez-galatasaray-demand-20m25m-repor/|title=Fiorentina eye former Tottenham defender Davinson Sanchez, Galatasaray demand €20m-25m - reports|first=Ivan|last=Kovbasa|date=1 May 2025|website=Tribuna.com}}</ref> He scored his first UEFA Champions League goal in a 5–2 victory over [[Juventus FC|Juventus]] on 17 February 2026.<ref>{{cite web |last=Poole |first=Harry |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/c70n42n83e5t |title=Galatasaray 5–2 Juventus |publisher=BBC Sport |date=17 February 2026 }}</ref>

==International career==
===Youth teams===
In November 2011, Sánchez was called up to dispute the [[2011 South American U-15 Championship]], where his team finished as runner-up behind Brazil; Sánchez was appointed as his team's captain for the tournament.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://fcf.com.co/index.php/2011/11/17/colombia-inicia-su-participacion-en-campeonato-sudamericano-sub-15/ | title=Colombia inicia su participación en Campeonato Sudamericano Sub-15 – Federación colombiana de fútbol }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://fcf.com.co/index.php/2011/11/30/duelo-de-lideres-e-invictos-en-sudamericano-sub-15/ | title=Duelo de líderes e invictos en Sudamericano Sub-15 – Federación colombiana de fútbol }}</ref>

Sánchez represented Colombia U-17 side at the [[2013 South American U-17 Championship]], where he appeared twice in the group stage.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.vanguardia.com/deportes/seleccion-colombia/definida-convocatoria-de-la-seleccion-colombia-sub-17-LYVL201921 | title=Definida convocatoria de la selección Colombia Sub-17 | date=28 March 2013 }}</ref>

On 6 January 2015, he was included in [[Carlos Restrepo (manager)|Carlos Restrepo]]'s 23-man list for the [[2015 South American U-20 Championship]], where Colombia secured qualification to the [[2015 FIFA U-20 World Cup]] and the [[Football at the 2016 Summer Olympics – Men's qualification (CONMEBOL–CONCACAF play-off)|Olympic play-off]] for [[2016 Summer Olympics|Rio 2016]] after finishing runner-up.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.winsports.co/seleccion-colombia/noticias/colombia-sub-20-definio-su-nomina-para-el-sudamericano-de-uruguay | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150107050540/http://www.winsports.co/seleccion-colombia/noticias/colombia-sub-20-definio-su-nomina-para-el-sudamericano-de-uruguay | archive-date=7 January 2015 | title=Colombia Sub 20 definió su nómina para el Sudamericano de Uruguay &#124; Win Sports }}</ref> On 6 May, Sánchez was named in Colombia final 23-man team for the U-20 World Cup, where his team exited the tournament in the round of 16 after falling to the [[United States men's national under-20 soccer team|United States]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://colombia.as.com/colombia/2015/05/11/futbol/1431379240_351386.html | title=Santos Borré encabeza los convocados al Mundial Sub 20 | date=11 May 2015 }}</ref>

Despite not disputing the Olympics, Sánchez appeared in both legs for the play-off series against the [[United States men's national under-23 soccer team|United States]], in which Colombia qualified to the Olympics for the first team since [[Football at the 1992 Summer Olympics|Barcelona 1992]] after finishing the series 3–2 on aggregate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/news/colombia-u-23-1-us-u-23-1-olympic-qualifying-playoff-match-recap|title=Colombia U-23 1, US U-23 1 &#124; Olympic Qualifying Playoff Match Recap &#124; MLSSoccer.com|website=mlssoccer|accessdate=14 April 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://soccer.nbcsports.com/2016/03/29/us-men-soccer-rio-olympics-miss/ | title=Colombia ends U.S. Olympic dreams 2-1; Yanks finish with 9 men | date=30 March 2016 }}</ref>

===Senior team===
Colombia manager [[José Pékerman]] called up Sánchez for a training squad with the senior [[Colombia national football team|Colombia]] squad in February 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.oximity.com/article/Pekerman-calls-up-local-players-with-a-1 |title=Pekerman calls-up local players with a view to WC qualifying |publisher=oximity.com |date=12 February 2016 |access-date=11 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181216074406/https://www.oximity.com/article/Pekerman-calls-up-local-players-with-a-1 |archive-date=16 December 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> On 26 August 2022, he was named in Colombia's squad for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification|2018 World Cup qualifiers]] against [[Venezuela national football team|Venezuela]] and [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.marca.com/futbol/colombia/2016/08/27/57c15f58e2704eaa0f8b4608.html | title=James encabeza la convocatoria de Colombia ante Venezuela y Brasil | date=27 August 2016 }}</ref> On 19 November, Sánchez made his debut against [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/match/_/gameId/431580 | title=Argentina vs. Colombia - Football Match Summary - November 15, 2016 - ESPN }}</ref>
[[File:Dávinson Sánchez, POL vs COL; FWC 2018.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Sánchez with Colombia at the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]]]]
In May 2018, he was named in Colombia's preliminary 35-man [[Colombia national football team|squad]] for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] in Russia.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/revealed-every-world-cup-2018-squad-23-man-preliminary-lists/oa0atsduflsv1nsf6oqk576rb |title=Revealed: Every World Cup 2018 squad – Final 23-man lists {{!}} Goal.com|access-date=5 June 2018}}</ref> In June 2018, he was named in Colombia's final 23-man squad for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] in Russia.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/soccer/colombia/story/3517715/colombia-name-world-cup-squad;-radamel-falcaojames-rodriguez-feature |title=Colombia name World Cup squad |publisher=ESPN|access-date=28 June 2018}}</ref> He played in all three group matches and their round of 16 match against [[England national football team|England]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/soccer/team/results/_/id/208/colombia |title=Colombia Results – 2018–19 {{!}} ESPN|publisher=ESPN|access-date=28 June 2018}}</ref>

In June 2019, he started in three of the four games at the [[2019 Copa América]], helped the team keep a clean sheet and beat Argentina for the first time in 12 years.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hitc.com/en-gb/2019/06/16/immense-tottenham-fans-react-to-davinson-sanchez-masterclass/ |title='Immense': Tottenham fans react to Davinson Sanchez 'masterclass' |date=16 June 2019|first=Shane |last=Callaghan|work=HITC }}</ref> The team however lost in the quarter-final against Chile after a penalty shoot-out.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thenationalnews.com/sport/football/alexis-sanchez-scores-winning-penalty-as-chile-beat-colombia-to-reach-copa-america-semi-finals-1.880394 |title=Alexis Sanchez scores winning penalty as Chile beat Colombia to reach Copa America semi-finals |author=Agence France-Presse|date=29 June 2019|work=The National}}</ref>

On 10 June 2021, Sánchez was included in [[Reinaldo Rueda]]'s 23-man squad for the [[2021 Copa América]] in [[Brazil]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://colombia.as.com/colombia/2021/06/10/futbol/1623347574_353706.html |title=Convocatoria Colombia Copa América: Entran Lucumí, Otero y Chará |website=AS Colombia |date=10 June 2021}}</ref> He featured in all of Colombia's matches as the team secured bronze after defeating [[Peru national football team|Peru]] 3–2 for the [[2021 Copa América knockout stage|third-place playoff]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://indianexpress.com/article/sports/football/colombia-beat-peru-3-2-in-the-third-place-match-at-copa-america-7397692/#:~:text=Colombia%20beat%20Peru%203%2D2%20on%20Friday%20in%20the%20third,Stadium%20in%20Rio%20de%20Janeiro | title=Colombia beat Peru 3-2 in the third-place match at Copa America | date=10 July 2021 }}</ref>

On 19 November 2022, Sánchez scored his first international goal in a 2–0 friendly win against [[Paraguay national football team|Paraguay]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.futbolred.com/seleccion-colombia/colombia-vs-paraguay-en-vivo-minuto-a-minuto-siga-aqui-los-goles-y-mejores-jugadas-170483 | title=Colombia invicta en era Lorenzo: Reviva el triunfo 2-0 vs Paraguay }}</ref>

On 14 June 2024, Sánchez was named into 26-man [[Colombia national football team|squad]] for the [[2024 Copa América]]. During the competition, Sánchez played every single match in the competition, and helped the team to get into a [[2024 Copa América final|Copa América final]] after 23 years, scoring a single goal, but being essential in the tournament.

